    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain bernoulli's principle and how it actually works to make an airplane wing lift up? like what's the deal with the shape of the airfoil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! Bernoulli's principle states that increased pressure in a fluid is related to decreased velocity. For an airplane wing, the shape of the airfoil, typically curved on top and flatter on the bottom, causes air to move faster over the top surface than the bottom, resulting in lower pressure on top and higher pressure on the bottom, thus creating lift. This allows the airplane to rise and stay airborne.",
      "source": "target",
