    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's hard to visualize though. can u explain it like something is actually happening to the air? like, what is the air physically doing when it hits the front of the wing and then has to deal with that curve?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Imagine the air is a crowd trying to stream past a stadium (the wing). As they approach, they're relatively calm (high pressure). As they reach the curved front (top of the wing), they can't easily get past the curve and squeeze through, causing them to slow down and form a high-pressure region due to reduced speed – that's Bernoulli's principle.\n\n\nAt the same time, the Coandă effect can be compared to a crowd being gently pulled along the course of the stadium (curved wing surface). This gentle guidance (air following the curve) would cause the crowd to travel faster (increase in pressure), but due to space restrictions, the crowd (air) still splits and drops pressure, which combined helps push the back (lower surface of the wing) upwards and the stadium itself (wing) lifts off the ground (creates lift).\n\n\n\nThe stadium (wing) rises as the front crowd supports the back, perfectly illustrating how these forces work together.",
      "source": "target",
